<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910726-0093</DOCNO><DOCID>910726-0093.</DOCID><HL>   Japan Says Exports   Of Vehicles Declined   By 1.9% in First Half   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>07/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5E</SO><CO>   J.MOT J.MZD NSANY TOYOY</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>AUTOMOBILES (AUT)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   TOKYO -- Japan's export of cars, trucks and buses slipped1.9% to 2.8 million in the first half of the year.   The Japan Automobile Manufacturers' Association said a9.8% decline in shipments to the U.S., the biggest importerof Japanese vehicles, pushed down overall exports. Meanwhile,exports to such regions as Asia, Europe and the Middle Eastshowed year-to-year growth.</LP><TEXT>   In June alone, a total of 448,936 motor vehicles wereexported, representing an 8.5% decline from June 1990.   Shipments to the U.S. totaled 950,598 in the first sixmonths of 1991, down 9.8%.   &quot;The downward trend of the vehicle exports to the U.S. islikely to continue for a while,&quot; an association officialsaid. But exports to Asia increased 6.2% in the first half to282,339 as economies in the area have been booming, he said.   Exports to the Middle East also rose, reflecting economicrecovery after the Persian Gulf War, which ended in lateFebruary, the official explained. Shipments of Japanesevehicles to the region totaled 133,883, up 2.7% from a yearearlier.   The official also said demand for vehicles has beenexpanding with the progress of economic liberalization inEastern Europe.   European nations imported a total of 985,391 Japanesevehicles, up 4.6%. The European Community nations aloneposted a 12.8% rise to 769,716, largely led by a strongincrease in exports to Germany, which now includes the formerEast Germany, he said.   Of the 2.8 million vehicles exported in the first half,passenger cars accounted for 2.2 million, down 1.2% from ayear earlier. Small-size car exports grew 3.3% to 1.6million, while medium-size car exports declined 12% to584,641. The decline in medium-size cars reflects slumpingexports to the U.S., the main importer of such models, theofficial said.   Truck exports totaled 613,478, down 4.7%, while busexports rose 20.6% to 23,364.   Exports by Toyota Motor Corp. slipped 0.7% to 846,045 inthe first half, while Nissan Motor Co. registered a 3%decline to 447,499. But Mazda Motor Corp.'s exports rose 6.1%to 426,629 while Mitsubishi Motors Corp. posted a 9.3% gain,to 313,957.</TEXT></DOC>